<TEXT>
hurricane erin continued its northward trek into 
cooler midatlantic waters friday with winds falling to 85 mph and 
forecasters predicting a gradual weakening over the weekend 
its only a threat to marine interests said national 
hurricane center forecaster todd kimberlain our forecast track is 
between greenland and ireland 
at 1030 pm edt erins center was near 430 north latitude and 
354 west longitude or about 310 miles westnorthwest of the 
westernmost azores the system was moving northeast at about 25 mph 
and was expected to weaken gradually over the next 24 hours 
the storm will probably lose its tropical characteristics over 
the north atlantic but that doesnt mean it will be harmless 
kimberlain said 
the storm will probably lose what forecasters call its tropical 
characteristics over the north atlantic but that doesnt mean it 
will be harmless kimberlain said a similar storm lashed great 
britain two years ago causing substantial damage 
erin became a named storm sunday night when sustained winds 
reached 39 mph it reached the 74 mph threshold for a hurricane 
tuesday 
there have been seven tropical depressions in the 1989 atlantic 
hurricane season which runs from june 1 to nov 30 erin is the 
fifth named storm and the third hurricane of the year 
</TEXT>
