<TEXT>
a 10yearold boy pleaded innocent friday 
to adult charges of criminal homicide in the march shooting of a 
7yearold girl who was riding a snowmobile in a lot adjacent to his 
home 
cameron kocher was 9 years old when police said he loaded his 
fathers 35caliber rifle pointed it out his parents bedroom 
window and shot jessica ann carr of gilbert in the back he has been 
free on 50000 bail 
cameron stood silently next to his attorney as monroe county 
judge ronald e vican addressing the boy as mr kocher 
explained the charges of criminal homicide aggravated assault and 
recklessly endangerment 
defense attorney charles hansford signed documents indicating 
camerons plea while the boy looked on and told the judge he had 
instructed the boy to stay quiet 
cameron stood before the judge with his arms folded occasionally 
looking at the ceiling and let out a heavy sigh as he turned to his 
parents after the proceedings ended 
jessica was riding on the back of a snowmobile march 6 in 
kresgeville with her friend and camerons nextdoor neighbor 
shannon ratti 13 when she was shot 
cameron was arrested two days later after police found the rifle 
with a telescopic sight a cut on the boys forehead and blood 
splattered in the room cameron said the rifle cut him when its 
recoil jammed the scopes eyepiece into his face 
in june vican refused to transfer camerons case to juvenile 
court saying the shooting was deliberate vicans decision followed 
four days of testimony from psychologists hired by the kochers and 
the state 
vican wrote in june that all four psychotherapists who examined 
cameron agreed he did not have any mental or emotional problems at 
the time of the shooting 
the psychologists disagreed however on whether cameron could 
understand the proceedings and participate in his defense the also 
disagreed on whether he could form the intent to kill 
cameron faced a prearraignment shortly after his arrest in 
march when bail was set at 50000 he has been free on bond since 
then 
assistant district attorney mark pazuhanich said in an interview 
he has ruled out seeking the death penalty he said if the boy is 
convicted punishment could range from probation in conjunction with 
psychiatric treatment to life imprisonment 
the defense has 30 days to file pretrial motions 
