why waltz when you can rock n roll 
wrote a visitor in the guest book at the medievalstyle castle of 
reputed cocaine trafficker camilo zapata vasquez 
the question reflects the fastlane philosophy obviously embraced 
by colombias wealthy drug lords and was revealed in the public 
confiscation of hundreds of their properties nationwide in an 
antinarcotics crackdown 
the sandstone castle ringed by formal gardens dominates a 
200acre compound of 10 buildings a dozen thoroughbred horses as 
well as goats ducks dogs and even a couple of flamingos visible 
from a nearby highway it has long been a landmark in chia a suburb 
13 miles north of bogota 
it was seized by the army this week and shown off to reporters 
on friday 
european and oriential antiques filled the castles richly 
appointed rooms lined with paintings statues and ceramic 
figurines beds were framed with crystal and bronze or four 
towering posters with marble bedside tables filled with electronics 
to open and shut doors and control video equipment 
a guest book provided a peek at the peculiar variety of people 
who visited the estate 
it is just one of many believed to have been owned by zapata 
vasquez even though he is considered a kind of secondstring 
smuggler lacking the householdname stature of reputed cartel 
bosses such as pablo escobar jorge ochoa and gonzalo rodriguez 
gacha 
the visitor who endorsed rock n roll signed his message 
apparently in jest m19 power m19 is the name accorded to a 
leftist guerrilla group operating in colombia although the 
traffickers are much more closely associated with rightwing death 
squads 
another visitor calling himself mad max wrote living by 
chance loving by choice and killing by profession 
an oct 10 1988 visitor named tuti wrote in a feminine hand 
happy birthday tomorrow theyll kill me and itll be your fault 
many women left their phone numbers after their signatures 
margarita zapata identified by army officials on the estate as 
zapatas sister was much more solemn may god and the virgin 
bless all of this and those who inhabit it 
the book also was signed by two men who identified themselves as 
local police station commanders two army lieutenants and an army 
captain two local mayors also signed one of them declaring few 
people can truly appreciate the history of this property 
a group of women from several embassies including yugoslavia 
