the library of congress said today it has 
received 135000 to help restore fire and waterdamaged books in a 
leningrad institution where one of the worst library disasters in 
history occurred 
the gift from readers digest will help experts counter the 
damage at the ussr academy of sciences library whose collection of 
20 million books manuscripts and periodicals was begun in 1714 by 
peter the great 
four million books were damaged or destroyed in a 19hour fire in 
february 1988 
the library of congress is a leader in developing techniques to 
rescue books threatened by decay or disaster 
james h billington librarian of congress and a russian expert 
went to leningrad after the fire to assess the damage and arranged 
for a protocol signed by the two institutions agreeing to preserve 
damaged materials and replace destroyed books 
peter waters a library of congress expert on the conservation of 
damaged book collections went to leningrad within six weeks of the 
fire 
billington welcomed the gift saying in a statement that it 
underscored the principle that library collections are truly 
international resources for humanity which all of us must support 
whenever one of them is threatened by destruction 
the library said the readers digest grant will finance 
equipment supplies and technical consultation to return to use many 
of the 200000 rare volumes that were frozen in an effort to arrest 
deterioration after the fire 
the leningrad institution is one of the worlds largest research 
libraries although not nearly as large as the library of congress 
which holds 86 million items 
the academy library is a major exchange partner for most us 
research libraries that collect russian and soviet materials every 
year several hundred us specialists in russians affairs visit 
there to do research 
a few months after the fire soviet historian and cultural 
activist dmitri likhachev said the disaster could have been 
prevented if officials had heeded warnings about the dilapidated 
condition of the soviet unions most prestigious book collections 
he said it pained him to see how rare books and art treasures 
that were spirited away by residents of leningrad to protect them 
from nazis who occupied the city in world war ii had been destroyed 
through negligence 
