<TEXT>
maybe its just her imagination 
but janice evans swears the train rumbling by her home has been 
louder since those hellish days in may when a train derailment was 
followed by a fiery pipeline explosion 
its like you stop every time the train passes to make sure 
nothings happening during the night its just twice as loud 
said mrs evans one of dozens of residents still looking for 
explanations and blame for the twin disasters 
beginning monday some of their questions may be answered when 
the national transportation safety board begins five days of 
hearings into the may 12 derailment of a southern pacific freight 
train and the may 25 explosion of a calnev pipe line co gasoline 
line near the tracks 
the two disasters killed six people and destroyed 15 homes 
focusing new attention on pipeline safety the ntsb hearing is 
intended to gather information to help the board determine a cause 
of the disasters and to make recommendations to prevent further 
accidents said board spokesman ted lopatkiewicz 
the board will pursue how workers calculated the load weight on 
the train the quality of locomotive brakes the cleanup of train 
wreckage near the calnev pipeline and the effectiveness of check 
valves in the line 
a final report with the probable cause is expected in at least 
six months 
in the meantime were just kind of in limbo said mrs evans 
whose house escaped serious damage but who continues to see a 
psychologist to help her deal with the emotional trauma caused by 
the disasters 
the ntsb hearing marks the latest in a series of public hearings 
probing the disasters 
in earlier sessions government officials called the nations 
pipeline safety programs inadequate while industry officials 
responded by pointing to the industrys relatively good safety 
record 
some of the sharpest criticism of the governments role in 
pipeline safety has come from democratic lawmakers who say 
regulators are burdened by staff shortages outofdate equipment 
and a tangle of weak and confusing laws 
the states pipeline safety division which acts as the federal 
governments surrogate in pipeline regulation employs 12 people to 
oversee thousands of miles of lines 
officials acknowledged that for several hours after the 
derailment they didnt even know of the existence of the duffy 
street pipeline which supplies 90 percent of las vegas gas and 
nearly all the jet fuel to george and edwards air force bases 
the federal office of pipeline safety said the calnev line may 
not have exploded after the train derailment had authorities been 
given the power to order a pressure test on the line to search out 
leaks and weak spots calnev did not perform the test saying it did 
not appear necessary at the time 
three check valves in the pipeline uphill from the rupture failed 
to close after the blast and gasoline flowed back into the flames 
ntsb inspectors found 
investigators discovered that the valves had not been inspected 
or maintained since they were installed along with the pipeline in 
1970 
calnev has since inspected its valves and taken other steps in 
the wake of disasters said spokesman richard kline 
calnev like other pipeline companies vigorously defends its 
practices by pointing to its safety record which shows that 
carrying fuel through pipelines is considerably safer than carrying 
fuel in tanker trucks or railroad cars 
