<TEXT>
thousands of civil rights demonstrators men 
clad in black women and children in white marched quietly upon the 
supreme court and the capitol today in a reprise of the naacps 
historic silent march of 1917 in new york city 
the washington march was concerned with one issue alone the 
supreme court and its recent hostile decisions diluting 
affirmative action and minority setaside programs said benjamin l 
hooks executive director of the naacp 
but the tone and style of the protest led by six drummers with 
muffled drums was fashioned after a march in new york city 72 years 
ago to protest segregation and the lynchings of blacks in the south 
on that occasion web dubois led 8000 people down fifth avenue 
in utter silence that day too the men dressed in black and the 
women and children in white 
us park police estimated the turnout when the march began at 
only 5000 but revised that figure to 35000 as the ranks swelled 
during the 1 hour procession to the capitol from washingtons mall 
us capitol police put the crowd which assembled on the capitol 
grounds at the end of the march at 18500 according officer greg 
nevitt 
hooks claimed from the podium that the march had drawn a turnout 
of 135000 
each of the marchers carried a printed affirmation which said 
we march to send a message to all people regardless of race 
color religion sex or ethnic orgin that we will not and cannot 
acquiesce quietly as an uncaring supreme court majority dismantles 
court ruling after court ruling and turns its face toward the dark 
past and away from the present and future 
and it said we march proudly in the footsteps of our brave 
sisters and brothers from another age who marched 72 years ago in 
silent witness against lynching discrimination segregation and 
racism for us not to march at this point in time would be a grave 
disservice to them 
the protest was aimed specifically at four decisions by the court 
this year in the view of civil rights lawyers the ruling in 
patterson vs mclean credit union sharply limited the previous power 
of minorities to sue private parties including schools for 
discrimatory practices similarly the courts decision in richmond 
vs j a croson co was seen as diluting job setaside programs and 
other affirmative action plans 
march organizers also assailed the decision in martin vs wilks 
which allowed white firefighters in birmingham ala to attack a 
consent decree calling for the promotion of blacks as a case of 
reverse discrimination the fourth ruling wards cove vs 
antonio was criticized as shifting the entire burden of proof in 
job discrimination cases to the victims of employer bias rather 
than requiring employers to demonstrate at the same time that 
their hiring practices furthered legitimate business interests 
the march culminated with a rally at the capitol where hooks and 
other civil rights leaders were scheduled to speak 
the rev jesse jackson the rev joseph lowery head of the 
southern christian leadership conference and mayors kurt schmoke of 
baltimore and marion barry of washington also were on the program 
on friday hooks talked about recent incidents of violence 
directed at his organization saying they have raised our level of 
concern not only for ourselves but for all other institutions and 
individuals who traditionally draw the wrath of racists 
several shots were fired july 19 into the naacp headquarters 
last monday a teargas bomb concealed in a package sent through 
the mail exploded at a regional office in atlanta 
these are the acts of terrorists hooks said people could 
have been behind those lighted windows in baltimore and in atlanta 
several innocent people including children and the elderly had to 
receive medical care 
if these acts were meant to frighten us or deter us from 
any course of action they failed completely we did not give in to 
terrorism when the ku klux klan was riding high and mighty and we 
will not give in to these latterday terrorists he said 
we are not looking toward bringing vast numbers of people to 
washington hooks said in this instance the medium is the 
message and the medium is the silent march 
the supreme court has often been the target of major 
demonstrations in the capital in recent years an estimated 325000 
turned out last spring to urge the court to stand by its 1973 
decision legalizing abortion however the court weeks later 
softened that ruling in a case seen as a victory for antiabortion 
forces 
