coasts of georgia and south carolina across the gulf coast region 
the tennessee valley and the lower mississippi valley into the 
southern plains and kansas as well as over the desert southwest 
the high temperatures and humidity pushed heat indexes above 105 
degrees from the tennessee valley across the lower mississippi 
valley into texas the heat index or apparent temperature is a 
measure of heat and humidity sensed by the body 
a reading above 105 is considered dangerous especially to those 
involved in prolonged outdoor physical activity 
the temperature reached 95 degrees at apalachicola fla on 
saturday afternoon breaking its record high for the day 
thunderstorms formed in the humid unstable air from the upper 
and middle mississippi valley across the western half of the ohio 
valley into the tennessee valley 
some of the storms brought heavy rainfall more than 1 inches of 
rain deluged lebanon tenn ashland ala received more than 1 
inches saturday afternoon 
showers and thunderstorms also were scattered across the southern 
atlantic coast states 
much of the west had cool temperatures due to a high pressure 
system centered over montana readings saturday afternoon were in 
the 50s and 60s from western north dakota across wyoming and the 
northern rockies 
temperatures in the 50s and 60s were also common across maine and 
northern new england 
the low temperature in the lower 48 states saturday morning was 
25 degrees at jackson wyo temperatures around the nation at 3 pm 
edt ranged from 56 degrees at arcata calif and crescent city 
calif to 101 degrees at beeville texas 
