<TEXT>
the united states and taiwan have signed an 
agreement that will enable federal authorities to track taiwanese 
fishing vessels by satellite in an effort to reduce illegal salmon 
fishing in the north pacific 
the agreement signed thursday calls for radio transponders to 
be installed in taiwanese boats allowing satellite surveillance of 
taiwans pacific fishing fleet it also permits us officials to 
board those ships 
in addition the pact provides for observers to monitor the 
driftnet fishermens impact on dolphin porpoise seal and other 
marine mammal populations 
tough negotiating pays off said us sen frank murkowski 
ralaska i believe signing this agreement lays the cornerstone 
for an overall effort to secure our fisheries and protect a most 
vital resource 
the united states has accused taiwan fishermen of using driftnets 
to deplete the north pacific of its rich marine resources 
especially the anadromous species of salmon that spawn in the united 
states 
conservationists have criticized the driftnets some of which are 
40 miles long for their incidental catches of thousands of sea 
birds seals and other animals 
some northwest fishermen said they liked what they heard friday 
about the pact 
its another step forward said barry collier of the pacific 
seafood processors association 
but at least one environmental group warned the agreement doesnt 
go far enough and that no such pact has been signed with south korea 
as a congressionally mandated deadline approaches 
you just cant trust these driftnetters said alan reichman 
pacific ocean ecology coordinator for greenpeace 
collier whose pacific seafood processors represents 85 percent 
of the processors in alaska washington and oregon estimated 7 
million salmon were taken illegally during 1987 
the agreement was signed for the united states by david laux 
chairman of the american institute in taiwan and ding moushih 
taiwans representative in washington dc diplomatic letters to 
finalize the agreement were signed friday 
the institute serves as the unofficial us embassy in taiwan 
the us government severed diplomatic ties with taiwan in 1978 
the key here is this monitoring equipment will go a long way to 
determining where those fish are caught and give us more confidence 
in managing the resource said vince curry of the alaska factory 
trawlers association 
by signing the pact taiwan beat a monday deadline set by a 1987 
law that threatened sanctions if japan south korea and taiwan did 
not agree to monitor their pacific fishing fleets and enforce bans 
on taking highseas salmon 
japan signed an agreement in june that called for the 
experimental use of transponders and a cadre of 47 observers nine 
american five canadian and 33 japanese to monitor driftnet damage 
to marine mammal populations 
similar details were not available friday for the pact with 
taiwan 
the us state department said friday that talks with the south 
koreans had been suspended until aug 29 similar agreements to 
those accepted by the japanese and taiwanese have been proposed 
yu yuhsien chairman of taiwans council of agriculture said in 
taipei that his government agreed to the pact for the sake of 
600000 fishermen on the island who depend on exports to the united 
states mostly of tuna and shrimp 
