<DOCNO> AP890826-0150 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
like kids tussling over an easter basket of 
goodies two federal agencies and the financial exchanges they 
regulate are squaring off over a new moneymaking product for 
investors known as a stock basket 
on one side are the stock exchanges and their overseer the 
securities and exchange commission created in the depths of the 
depression to regulate stocks and bonds and protect the people who 
invest in them 
on the other side is the newer commodity futures trading 
commission and its charges the boisterous markets that deal in 
commodities such as soybeans pork bellies and silver 
the product at issue is technically called an index 
participation but it resembles a basket of stocks because it 
allows investors to buy or sell something with a value tied to broad 
stock market indexes such as the standard amp poors 500 thats why 
its also called a stock basket 
a week ago a federal appeals court in chicago ruled the sec 
overstepped itself in authorizing three exchanges in new york 
philadelphia and chicago to trade stock baskets 
the 7th us circuit court of appeals held that the new financial 
instruments are futures contracts and should be regulated by the 
cftc throwing doubt on the legitimacy of the baskets traded on the 
stock exchanges 
its like being married for five years and finding out the 
preacher wasnt licensed says amex president kenneth r leibler 
and if you want to get married again you have to do it in a 
different state 
while the new products havent been a raging success since 
trading began may 12 in new york and philadelphia some observers 
they represent the future of the securities industry 
new product development became particularly important after the 
1987 stock crash which depressed the business of many investment 
firms and forced them to seek ways of luring investors back 
the american and philadelphia exchanges as well as the chicago 
board options exchange thought one answer would be stock baskets 
unlike stocks investors never actually buy the securities that 
make up a stock index and therefore have no ownership rights but 
unlike commodity futures theres no settlement or termination date 
the basket can be held indefinitely 
for example an investor could buy a basket tied to the sampp 500 
index when it has a value of 300 a monetary value is assigned to 
each contract usually sold in lots of 100 if the value was 30 or 
onetenth the sampp 500 index the basket would be worth 3000 and 
if the index went up 10 points the investor would make a profit of 
100 because the lot of 100 was now worth 3100 
but the stock baskets also represent a challenge to similar 
products offered by the two major futures exchanges in chicago the 
chicago board of trade and the chicago mercantile exchange 
those two exchanges claimed the stock baskets ought to be 
regulated by the cftc and the appeals court agreed saying the law 
creating the cftc clearly gave it authority in this case 
our feeling is the cftc is best equipped to regulate futures 
products because it has the expertise said michael oconnell a 
spokesman for the board of trade 
to us rep edward markey dmass chairman of the house finance 
subcommittee who has tried unsuccessfully to push market reform 
legislation the ruling highlights the problems inherent in this 
turf battle between the sec and the cftc said a markey spokesman 
but joanne medero the cftcs general counsel said i dont 
think the people here feel it is a turf battle not on the 
commissioner or staff level the turf battle may be more between the 
securities exchanges and the commodities exchanges rather than the 
agencies which is fine thats competition 
the cftc did file court papers in the chicago lawsuit stating its 
view that stock baskets are futures contracts and if the ruling is 
appealed ms medero said we would reiterate our position 
spokesmen for both stock and futures exchanges stopped short of 
saying another agency might not treat them fairly but indicated they 
preferred to deal with the one theyve known for years 
stock exchange officials noted that margins the amount of money 
or collateral that must be put up to buy securities are less 
stringent in the futures markets 
under cftc rules said nicholas giordano president of the 
philadelphia exchange the stock basket wont be a product that 
appeals to the public investor the man in the street itll be 
more speculative have higher risk and would not enjoy the 
protection of public investor rules that have been cultivated by the 
sec for 50 years 
the sec has yet to announce whether it will appeal the ruling by 
the chicago federal court 
i really cant tell you until we do it said paul gonson the 
secs solicitor although he confirmed that the agency was 
discussing alternatives with the exchanges 
</TEXT>
